comments: Regrade requests for males tend to be for higher point values, while those from females tend to be for lower point values (just one or two points).  Perhaps this is just my impression from thinking of a few cases that stand out in my mind.

In the three semesters I have as GTA, I have received about 3 regrade requests from men and 1 from a woman.  All in the first and second semester, none in the current semester.  In the case of male students, 2 of them asked me where they had a mistake, and the other male and the female student emailed me writing that they do not understand why they got such a low grade, and that they think they deserve more points.    Men that ask for regrade generally are good students, and they actually deserved more points that I graded.    The female student I regraded was a regular student (her overall grade was around 72% at that moment), and she in the email included the fact that she needs at least B to enter in the business school.  Sincerely, she did not deserved that regrade, but I did it because I would feel bad if someone (man or woman) cannot enter in the school he/she wants for a couple of points.  If a male student with the same argument (he "needs more points to enter in the business school") emailed me, I would regraded him exactly the same, helping him.
My male students tend to act a bit more offended that they have to ask for regrades than my female students, who are a bit more emotionally dependent on their grades.

Female students tend to present a better understanding of material when they are asking for a regrade when compared to their male counterparts. More effort in placed on regrades by female students than male students.
I teach in a majority female major, few male students, and have not experienced any regrade requests from male students at CSU (after 2 full semesters and 1 nearly complete semester)
Not enough data - I teach small classes. I have however noticed an upward trend in the number of male students requesting higher grades, while females seems to be holding steady.
This survey has so many typos that I cannot understand many of the questions.  I also see a ton of bias in the questions.  It truly surprises me that this made it through IRB

It seems like males tend to be more aggressive with female professors when asking for regrades than with male professors. As a female professor, I hear about regrade requests much more often from other female professors than male professors.
No.
No-- We just have more female majors
I don't change grades, so gender doesn't play a role
No.
The differences are not gender related so much as they are ability related.  High caliber students who are driven only by graded outcomes tend to ask for regrades more often than not.

I have never had a female ask for a regrade - only males who choose not to show up to class and then expect to make a good grade. I also find that male students cheat more often than females in my classes.
None that I can think of.
Not that I can think of, but this survey is interesting and I will likely think about it more in the future...

The male students tend to procrastinate and ask for permission to submit late work.  Female students often wait til end of semester and use emotional distress and personal circumstances as a reason as to why they should be allowed to make up work.  While I am certain there are legitimate issues,  I feel some students abuse a resource we make available for those who have real needs.  I have also had a female student go to my chair with false accusations against me because I did not allow make up work.  My chair supported my position but it was quite stressful.
Male students are less likely to accept no for an answer. I never give in, but I have resorted to referring all belligerent students to Student Resolution Services.
Questions asked/confrontation. Males would be more accusatory: "you didn't tell us this," while females were more forgiving
I have only had one student ask for a regrade at any point in the semester (female) in 16 years of teaching. The survey required me to answer above 4 questions, but I would have left them blank.

The way male vs female students ask for re-grades. Female students tend to use phrases such as "sorry to bother you" or "I think maybe there was an error, but I'm not sure" where as male students are direct and sometimes rude, blaming a poorly written exam question for the reason for their grade. Female students tend to take responsibility for the grade, even if it is not their fault (miscalculation in points, eg) while male students tend to blame the wording but not take responsibility for their incorrect answers. This is all in relation to requesting regrades.
None.
Men tend to ask when it relates to passing where women's requests relate to the grade itself
no

Entitlement from males. Expectation that not paying attention in class will result in an individual / personalized lecture to either bring grade up or improve final project. Males tend to argue individual points and questions whereas females tend to request an extra credit assignment or way of making up missing points, males want you to simply add points.
not responding to the question, just want to say that I try to teach to minimize such requests, don't get many of them, and don't remember the details well.
The majority of students taking my classes are female.  Only 1-2% are male

Male students are very aggressive in terms of their language and behavior, often trying to intimidate or dominate me both in writing and in person. These students rarely have read or followed the procedures for making regrade requests that are outlined in the syllabus. Female students tend to use the strategies and techniques they've learned from class (I teach communication) to make their requests and follow the procedures outlined on the syllabus. They are respectful of me and are willing to discuss their work and learn from it rather than insisting specifically on an improvement to their grade.
none
Male students tend to present their regrade requests more nicely than female students do.
Males may be more likely to assume that the low exam result is due to grading error and females may be more likely to assume that the low exam result is due to their performance.

The male students tend to have more of an aggressive attitude with an expectation that things change more than the female students. The male students usually approach the regrade with a defensive attitude.
emotional reactions from females
I have more women asking for (undeserved) passing grades but men ask too.  I have more women asking for regrades that are deserved.  But I also tend to have more women in my classes.
None that come to mind, no.
No

In this particular major there are MANY more male students than female students.  The female students definitely tend to be shyer (less willing) to ask for things like regrade requests -- or very reasonable coaching/teaching assistance -- than the male students.
My department has a very high male enrollment compared to female enrollment, so I have more male students that ask for grade reviews than females due to enrollment.
Female students seem to ask about regrading more promptly while male students often procrastinate before reviewing their work and asking for regrading.
No, as I have only had 1 (male) student request a regrade. Please be careful with my data.
N/A
none
Generally I get fewer regrade requests from female students at the end of the semester because they seem to have their act together better than some of the male students.
Their approaches in asking are very different; I said "as aggressive" because they tend to be as common and as insistent, but actual language/tone/body language tends to be a bit more aggressive.

Male students typically asked for regrades at the end of the semester without any reasoning to support why they believed their final grades should be changed. I had no female students that asked for their final grades to change. I was required to answer questions 4 and 6 which were about female students and their final semester grades even though this wasn't applicable.

Students who requests regrades based on a logical analysis of the grading rubric appear to be highly performing students, regardless of gender identity. Likewise, underperforming students who request regrades may be passionate about their personal challenges and in linking why they are underperforming to factors outside of the classroom. I note this distinction with more prevalence than a tangible divide in the student's gender identity. Interesting survey!
I have observed that more females ask, but that they are usually doing better in the class than males that don't ask.

Female students are more persistent (on average) and will ask several times using multiple arguments as to why their grade needs to be changed.    Male students tend to have an air of expectation that their request will be granted and incredulity when it is denied.  Female students tend to have an air of hope when asking and resignation when it is denied.
No
It tends to align with future professional school aspirations.......thus, if there are more female students that year or more male students percentages will change
I'm really not sure. See, I tend NOT to consider my student's gender when interacting with them. The TA training puts a large emphasis on this.

I have significantly more female students than male so you should take my gender differences answers with a grain of salt. The only two male students who have asked for an end of the semester grade change were student #1: very smart but lots of mental health issues and #2: not particularly intelligent/didn't work too hard but persuasive. The women more frequently ask for during-semester regrades and this is general due to them having missed assignments or tests due to health issues, work conflicts, roommate issues, mental health problems, etc
Female students often have more excuses

One thing you didn't ask, my class has more females than males, but about the same number of males ask for re grades as females at the end, and more during the semester, but this represents a higher percentage of males asking than females.  At least I think this didn't get asked.

I have never really kept track of the male/female differences for my classes, and have not noticed gender differences. I do not change grades after the semester has ended (unless it is to correct an error in entering a grade in the gradebook).
No
None. Our discipline has very few women in most of the classes.

Usually, a re-grade request by male students to me (a female instructor) is more about questioning if I had the right or knew what I was doing when I graded them thusly. A female re-grade request is often focused more on trying to understand what they did wrong and if some of what they put was right.      As such, that is why I have noticed that re-grades for males has failed more often that females when I am the instructor.     Additionally, re-grade requests often get lower grades because I have no mercy/leniency for casual mistakes.  When I have re-graded an assignment/quiz, I warn them that I will re-grade the whole document with a careful eye.  That yields (often) a loss of points rather than gain of points.
No.

Females tend to phrase their regrade requests as requests for confirmation that the scoring was accurate.  Males tend to bring examples of work that they believe is similar that received higher scores.
Not that I've seen
Male students showed a more deserving attitude when they made the requests.
No
The male students who have asked for such changes have often referred to me by my first name or as "mrs..." rather than Dr. or Professor.
no
In my experience, certain upper level Biology classes have more females than males.  However, there doesn't seem to a drastic ability or behavior difference between the male and female students.
I have very, very few regrade requests, so it is hard to generalize from such a tiny sample.

It is harder to get men students to give up.  They either won't leave my office until I give them a point or two, or at the end of the semester they are more likely to keep sending emails instead of accepting my first response.  I also seem to have particular trouble with some men international students.
no
no

While I've had both male and female students ask pre and post grades being posted they're more inclined to ask pre final grade thinking that once it's posted it can't be changed.  Again while both male and female students have asked at both points, I've only ever had male students threaten to do a grade appeal if I didn't change the grade.  About 3 male students have threatened in the last 5 years and only one followed through (the committee determined the grade should not be changed from that which was originally awarded)
Female students tend to cry or express nervous/anxious behavior when asking for regrades
I dont receive regrade requests during the semester, but the last page wouldn't allow for that option for each question.
Please take into account that in my discipline (STEM) there is a higher ratio of male than female students, so naturally more requests come from male.
N/A

Hard to say, my classes are 80-90% male.  Not great for gathering your desired data.  One thing I have really noticed is that end of semester requests are almost always international students and they are much more aggressive than other students.

My experience has been that poor male students want a bump at the end of the semester to pass, while female students who want a bump want to get the highest GPA possible. Male students tend to use threats more (e.g. I am going to complain to your dean, some office at CSU) or involve their parents. Generally, most students are great, but some recognize that they can take advantage of some of the staff at CSU that exist to help students.
Since I am female, I have had male students, asking for regrades, take off their glasses to show me how beautiful their eyes are. Their grade remained the same, however.
No. Perhaps not enough female students to form a significant sample.
Female students who request regrades are sometimes more emotional (visibly upset, tears) in presenting their request than male students who request regrades.

Male students tend to be way more aggressive ("I deserve an A," "do you know who I am?") whereas female students are more motivated by a desire to get it right ("I do not think you understood the argument that I was making and I think if I explain it to you I can persuade you that I do know the material.")
Female students are typically quicker to offer the details explaining their need of the regrade than male students.

Male students often ask for regrading with an adamant belief that they have been wronged when they have not been wronged (and often performed at a lower level). In fact, female students request tend to be fewer and more justified than their more common male peers. As a male instructor, male students approach me with regrade requests that are either forceful (but not hostile) or with an ease suggesting a camaraderie among male instructors and students. In conversations with female and gender-fluid colleagues and grad students, this tone appears to be uncommon and their interactions are more hostile.

There are gender non-conforming students who have asked.    Main difference I have experienced is that students form the racially dominant group are more aggressive and entitled.    Males may be more apt to ask in general.  However, women racially identified as 'white' have been aggressive.

Male students tend to be more pleading, at least through email. I have gotten a lot of, for lack of a better term "ass-kissing" from male students as well as phrases like "can you please just make an exception this one time," "I need to do well for such and such a reason," or "can you find it in the kindness of your heart to help me out."

Male students tend to be much more aggressive along two dimensions: (1) willingness to ask for regrade over minor issues (grade change, when it happens, is much smaller); (2) aggressiveness in their behavior -- they just assume the fault is mine, not theirs.

Males tend to argue cases of, “It COULD be the answer I selected too, if you think about it.” (This caused me to add in phrases like, “According to chapter three in the book...” at the beginning of a question to avoid that.    Males nitpicked a lot like that.    Males also seemed more panicked at the end of the semester.     Just a note: I’ve never had a female student ask for a regrade. There was no option to bypass those questions in any way to make sense.
No

Typically, the male student will try to go over my head to the basic course director to appeal a grade. I have never had a female student appeal to the basic course director. I, generally, find that my male students miss more assignments due to lack of preparedness and organization.

I have not received a single grade inquiry or change request at the end of the semester from a female student. Only male students make these requests, one of whom aggressively emailed me over the course of an entire day after he failed the final exam. In my estimation, male students who do considerably less work and devote less effort to class are often or always the students who expect their grades to change at the end of the semester. Incidentally, these students are also the only students to comment that my grading is “tough” on end of semester evaluations.

This also varies culturally, as I teach a lot of international students, and male international students are a lot more likely to ask for regrades. In my classes, there's not really a place for regrades--instead, improvement on the next paper is focused on--and male students tend to overemphasize their ability to themselves, and at times are more likely to keep trying to rely on that ability rather than use resources (office hours, writing center, classmates) to help them improve.  While there are some regrade requests during the semester (such as from international male students), the panic tends to come at the end of the semester for them, whereas female students tend to ask if points were missed for a specific aspect (and at times it might have been my error, which is where a slight grade change might be made). Regrades at the end of the semester don't really happen, but I do round up if it affects a letter grade or plus/minus, so a few of the students who ask are in a position to benefit from that, but most male students who ask are panicked because of a scholarship that is GPA dependent, but also it's too late and too much of a change in grade needed to do anything.
Not that I have observed.
No
No differences are observed perhaps because of firm course policy of not regrading.

Female students tend to use email to address the complaint and do so in a more formal manner. Male students seem to be more emotionally charged which has resulted in more male students having cried during the review of assessments. I actually cannot recall a single female students crying in a face-to-face meeting about graded work.  I would say that the method of asking for regrading takes two pathways. The first is to specify a portion of the assignment which was marked down and support an argument in favor of a different grade. This is usually more successful approach. The other method is to just ask for a better grade. Not a good strategy. I would say that neither strategy seems to be favored by either gender.
When asking about grades, females generally seem to be more professional, cordial, and understanding than males.
No difference
Aggressive male behavior and refusal to accept feedback on inappropriate tone in requesting changes, particularly from female instructors.

I think males and females tend to ask for a regrade during the semester only when they see an error in grading. After the semester, I think maybe students try to get a better grade just b/c they need it or are close to a grade point cut off. I think the nr of males and females are the same. When this happens, females tend to write really extensive requests (they try harder), males tend to be shorter in their requests (I read that as less aggressive) and tend to accept the (negative) decision more easily.
Male regrade requests generally reflect a sense of entitlement, e.g. a male student is more likely to say they “deserve” an A, relative to a female student.
